# Grafana frontend conventions

Follow the patterns already used in the surrounding code. These rules are scoped to
frontend TypeScript/React files via the `globs` above, so they only load into context
when you are actually working on frontend code.

## Components

- Use function components with hooks. Do not add new class components.
- Keep components focused; colocate a `ComponentName.test.tsx` next to new components.

## Styling

- Use Emotion via the `useStyles2(getStyles)` hook from `@grafana/ui`. Define a
  `getStyles(theme: GrafanaTheme2)` function and read colors/spacing from the `theme`
  (e.g. `theme.spacing(2)`, `theme.colors.text.secondary`). Never hardcode hex colors.
- Do not introduce inline `style={{ ... }}` for anything theme-related.

## State & data fetching

- Use Redux Toolkit slices (not legacy connect/mapStateToProps) for app state.
- Use RTK Query for data fetching where a service already exposes it.

## Internationalization

- All user-facing strings must be wrapped with the `t()` helper from `@grafana/i18n`
  (see existing panels, e.g. `public/app/plugins/panel/stat/module.tsx`). After adding
  strings, run `make i18n-extract`.

## Logging

- Never use `console.log`/`console.warn`/`console.error` in shipped frontend code.
  Use the structured logger from `@grafana/runtime`
  (`logInfo`, `logWarning`, `logError`, or `createMonitoringLogger(source)`).

## Tests

- Write tests with React Testing Library + Jest. Run a single file with
  `yarn jest --no-watch <path>` (the default `yarn test` script enables `--watch`).
